Written evidence from the defaultRdefaultoyal defaultCdefaultollege of defaultGdefaulteneral defaultPdefaultractitioners (LTC 93)default&#xa0;defaultThe Royal College of General Practitioners (RCGP) is the largest membership organisation in
default&#xa0;
defaultthe United Kingdom solely for GPs. Founded in 1952, it has over 46,000 members who are committed to improving patient care, developing their own skills and promoting general practice as a discipline. We are an independent professional body with enormous expertise in patient–centred generalist clinical care. 
default&#xa0;defaultExecutive Summary default&#xa0;
defaultWe welcome the opportunity to contribute to this Inquiry. Caring for patients with long term conditions is at the core of day-to-day practice for GPs, with such patients representing over 50% of GP appointments
default.
default 
defaultGPs have a vital role to play in supporting those living with long term conditions because:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe increasing prevalence of long term conditions is one of the biggest challenges currently facing our health and social care systems. We need a shared vision for how we adapt to meet this challenge at a time when the UK's population is ageing and funding is predicted to remain flat.
default 
defaultT
defaulthe following will be vital to delivering a successful strategy on long term conditions:
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default
default              
defaultShiftdefaultingdefault resources into primary care: defaultThe primary care team
default will be vital to any successful future model of support for patients with long term condi
defaulttions. H
defaultowever, the system of funding for NHS services remains skewed towards hospitals care. Over 2010/11 and 2011/12 spending on general practice fell in real terms (compared to real terms increases for hospital care, mental health and community health services). If we are serious about anticipating the 
defaultcare needs of those with long term conditions and putting them in control of their care, we must look at how we can provide primary care – where 90% of patient contact with the NHS takes place – with better resources.
default&#xa0;
defaultResponse to specific issues highlighted by the Select Committee default&#xa0;default1. Defining 'long-term conditions'default&#xa0;
defaultGiven the Committee's stated aim to review the definition of long-term conditions, RCGP offers the following proposed wording:
default&#xa0;
defaultA long term condition is any medical condition
default that cannot currently be cured but can be managed with the use of medication and/or other therapies. This is in contrast to acute 
defaultc
defaultonditions which typically have a finite duration such as a respiratory infection, an inguinal hernia or a mild episode of depression.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs with many concepts in healthcare, there are likely to be many different interpretation
defaults
default of what constitutes a long term condition. Ultimately, the best means of defining what is an
defaultd
default isn't a long term condition, and making decisions about 
defaultcare requirements
default, is as part of a conversation between an individual and their doctor (usually a GP). 
default&#xa0;
default2. Moving care out of hospitals and into the community default–default are we ready?default&#xa0;
defaultI
defaultt is vital that in the coming years we see a major shift towards managing and planning 'whole person' patient care in the community, moving away from the focus on treating individual 
defaultepisodes
default of illness in secondary care. The 
defaultincreasing
default prevalence of long term conditions and multiple morbidity mean that the ‘status quo’ is not an option
default.
