default(iii) Workforce planning and trainingdefault&#xa0;
defaultContinuing to move care out of hospitals and into the community has significant implications for the primary care workforce. The Centre for Workforce Intelligence has highlighted that the GP workforce is not growing quickly enough to meet predicted increases in demand
default.
default 
defaultThe 
defaultCfWI
default has recommended a 17% increase in recruitment into GP speciality training, which will necessitate a reduction in recruitment into training in hospital-based specialties. We need a robust long term approach to workforce planning, led by Health Education England, to ensure that patients with long term conditions are supported by an adequate GP workforce.
defaultAs the needs of patients change 
default–
default and as the rise of multiple morbidities 
defaultcontinues to lead to 
defaultincreases 
defaultin 
defaultthe complexity of care 
default–
default we also need to ensure that GP training reflects this. The RCGP's proposals for extending the length of GP training from 3 (currently the shortest of any medical specialty) to 4 years
default 
defaultare in the process of being considered by the Government, with a decision by health Ministers across all four nations of the UK expected in late 2013. Extending and enhancing GP training will mean that GPs of the future are better equipped to provide care and support to those with long term conditions.
